Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the euro area is the rapidly rising food prices.
In the 13 countries of the eurozone, inflation was higher than expected in November - after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are assumed only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the American, British and Canadian Central Bank, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the central government. At their discretion, the cut in interest rates would encourage rising commodity prices and the slight decline in unemployment to boost the formation of an inflation spiral.
The ECB is seeking to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least slightly at the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in a daily fandle: inflation must be "agreed" in order to exclude action later.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate in Germany reached a twelve-year record high in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The increase in food and energy prices are responsible for the rise in inflation in the euro area.
MATIF wheat prices increased by 88 percent, and soybeans prices also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a considerable inflation in 2007 for edible oil and dairy products.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but they are expected to decline to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expected to achieve a 3% inflation rate, but the annual average rate estimated at 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to lower interest rates twice.
