In many places, disinfectants are saved
This year more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals, which were due to an improper handling of antibiotics.
Hygienic conditions in hospitals, overloading of beds, overloading of personnel - all factors which are not exactly beneficial to containment of infections, so the leading physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of the János Hospital, an MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The bacterium, resistant to antibiotics, was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection.
The injured of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but shortly afterwards the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation has not yet been performed because of the bacterium, which is still in the patient's body.
Until 10. In December this year, 1,094 infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, including Karolina Böröcz, head doctor of the National Epidemiology Centre.
So so many infections triggered by multi-resistant pathogens were certainly registered in hospitals, but the number of unreported cases is likely to be higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were triggered by MRSA, the Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their noses without it cause a disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin inflammation or wounds) usually react well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the funds are too highly dosed or used improperly, antibiotic-resistant are formed from the well-responding bacteria, which spread quickly under corresponding conditions in hospitals.
Especially in patients with a weakened or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical head of the János Hospital, the MRSA infection is not special, such incidents belong to the daily health routine.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi was looked at - MRSA does not exist only where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff wears rubber gloves and masks in their care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - says Tibor Nyulasi.
When they are sent to the hospital, patients are examined for MRSA, but an infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of the infections in hospitals triggered by MRSA would be preventable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable for containing the formation or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection is mainly found in hospitals and old people's homes, the hospitals should examine the delivered patients and immediately isolate MRSA infected persons.
In Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not so often practised.
Not least because there are no subsidies for this investigation on the part of the state health insurance company.
Most cases therefore only come to light if the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, says the medical director of the Epidemiology Center.
On the part of the European Union, there are strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests are necessary so that no resistance to the remedy can form, but this directive is not always adhered to by hospitals.
According to Karolina Böröcz, microbiological sampling is even rare among patients in outpatient or in basic care.
The disinfectants are saved
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most frequently transferred by one patient to another by nursing staff.
This is precisely why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks, is of great importance, but there are also considerable shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in the local hospitals there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patient.
The rooms are even often overcrowded, the beds are narrowly lined up, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 metres between them from an epidemiological point of view.
Unfortunately, as Karolina Böröcz continues to point out, there are unfortunately even savings in disinfectants in disinfectants, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that encourage the development of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less frequent there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are complied with, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government Programme against MRSA
MRSA infections get under control caused the health insurance company enormous costs, therefore they are combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government programme.
According to initial signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has made it one of its priorities for the prevention of the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA), as well as the prevention of infections in hospitals.
