New fears of natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is smoulding between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk of Russian exports of fuel to be affected by fuel to Western Europe.
Most of Russia's exports of natural gas to the European Union (EU) are routed by Ukraine and every dispute between the two nations is being observed very closely.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for the natural gas, it will charge higher transit fees from Russia.
A previous conflict between the two states reduced deliveries to the EU states last year.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow is happening at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian government gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine has to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be calculated more, as the company has agreed to pay up to 50% additionally for natural gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine has to pay 40% more for imports from Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks," said Ukraine's Minister of Economy Anatoly Kinakh of the news agency Reuters.
"The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine."
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom shortened deliveries to Ukraine.
This led to a case of exports to Western Europe, driving up prices drastically.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas resources, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
The consequence is that Gazprom complements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "musss control foreign workers"
The Scottish State Health Service must improve the controls of the criminal records for workers from outside Europe, said a member of the supervisory body.
The recommendation of the main financial controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought together with the attack on Glasgow airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish public health service does not have exact ideas about the number of its foreign employees.
However, his report pointed out that other important controls were carried out correctly on a sample of five health authorities.
The main financial controller examined personnel recruited outside the countries of the European economic area, as a result of the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after an off-road vehicle was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video transmission at Old Bailey in October, and was charged with the alleged car bomb attack in the UK.
The state health service is expected to carry out checks in advance of hiring foreign staff to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the UK.
Although health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review criminal records, the Agency does not have the responsibility to obtain this information outside the UK.
The auditor's report now states, among other recommendations, that the Board should pick up on guidelines for the extract from penal register that helps employers with checks in various countries.
"Although we found references to these checks in some personnel documents, they were not routinely carried out," the report stated.
Black said Scottish health authorities would be following their investigation guidelines to a large extent before employment, but added, "Our report shows areas where the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information about the number of foreign health workers is available."
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations in the run-up to the employment of potential NHS employees would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report states that NHS' current pre-employment tests are working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say that they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of them doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number was likely to be higher, also because the boards have difficulty identifying those employees who are on leave for an indefinite period.
The investigation also found that established control procedures were largely observed by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian.
This includes passport, work permits and qualification controls.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policy and guidelines for checks before starting employment for foreign staff in the NHS.
The Secretary for Health Nicola Sturgeon said: "It was a matter for me to carry out this work in the face of the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport."
It added that the Scottish Government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that the best practices in updated guidelines on check-up inspections would be reflected in the run-up to the employment of all employees, including those from abroad, would be planned to be published next month.
