These are not Warhol's boxes
If you connect the terms Sweden and the wooden box, think of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Or after all?
Currently, manufactured wooden chests in Sweden throw dark shadows on Warhol's list of works.
The majority of the ninety-four Brillo boxes of "type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago fueled the authenticity of Andy Warhol's brillo boxes of 1968, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm is now becoming a sobering result: The six "Brillo boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén bequeathed to the Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - and probably also the most of the a hundred types.
The prehistory is nested, a confusing concatenation of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard box of the soap powder "Brillo".
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - presented hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these did not come (for cost reasons) by Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo carton factory.
They were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission to have a few Brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden in 1968, which were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of around fifteen boxes, which at that time were rightly included in the art and auction history as authorized as original Andy Warhol-Brillo boxes called "Typ Stockholm".
Some of them have earned more than 100,000 dollars at auction.
The problem is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were only found in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg produced.
At that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, head conservator at the Moderna Museet, in addition to the six museum's own Brillo boxes, also examined three from Swedish private property, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press chipboards were first primed and shelved, after which white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the pressboard with a painting roll without a primer - it is not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's brillo boxes," says the director of Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to another conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in his collection as copies/e exhibition material."
In July, however, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "serious accusations" made in the case of soap powder boxes.
But since then, they have been enforced in relentless silence.
